{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502042"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1819"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1819"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.04,0.62,0.06,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75672"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1819"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61190"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"207"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37068"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41930"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75672"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe abdominal pain. He is diagnosed with a perforated peptic ulcer and undergoes emergency surgery for repair of the perforation. He has a minor wound infection and is commenced on piperacillin-tazobactam. Three days after the operation he becomes severely agitated and confused, with visual hallucinations of insects crawling on the walls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears disorientated to time, place, and person. He has marked tremor of his hands and profuse diaphoresis. His vital signs reveal a pulse rate of 145/min, blood pressure 185/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Blood tests show sodium 128 mmol/L (135-145), potassium 3.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0), and magnesium 0.6 mmol/L (0.7-1.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of depression managed with sertraline, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease treated with tiotropium and salbutamol. He drinks \u0027a few beers\u0027 daily but denies heavy alcohol use. Post-operatively, he has been receiving regular paracetamol, as-needed oxycodone, and regular haloperidol for agitation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his deterioration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serotonin syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Alcohol withdrawal delirium","Septic encephalopathy","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex diagnostic challenge with multiple potential causes of delirium. However, the constellation of marked autonomic instability (tachycardia, hypertension, hyperthermia), visual hallucinations, confusion, and timing of onset (3 days post-op) is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcohol withdrawal delirium\u003C/strong\u003E (delirium tremens). The patient\u0027s minimisation of alcohol use is common, and his electrolyte derangements (particularly hypomagnesaemia) support chronic alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered given the combination of sertraline and piperacillin-tazobactam. However, serotonin syndrome typically presents with hyperreflexia, clonus, and myoclonus, which are not described here. The visual hallucinations would also be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnticholinergic toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E from medications like tiotropium could cause confusion and autonomic instability. However, it typically presents with dry mucous membranes, urinary retention, and mydriasis, contrasting with the profuse sweating seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeptic encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is possible given the post-operative wound infection. However, the marked autonomic instability and visual hallucinations are more characteristic of delirium tremens. Additionally, the infection is described as minor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E could occur with haloperidol use. However, it typically presents with lead-pipe rigidity and would be unusual to develop so rapidly. The visual hallucinations and profuse diaphoresis are more consistent with delirium tremens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe case is made more complex by the presence of multiple medications that could contribute to delirium, electrolyte abnormalities, and infection. However, the specific pattern of severe autonomic instability, visual hallucinations, and timing strongly suggest delirium tremens as the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Alcohol withdrawal delirium (delirium tremens) typically presents 48-96 hours after last drink with autonomic instability, confusion, and hallucinations.","Post-operative patients with alcohol use disorder may have multiple concurrent causes of delirium requiring careful clinical assessment.","The presence of visual hallucinations and marked autonomic instability helps distinguish delirium tremens from other causes of post-operative delirium."],"references":["Jesse S, Br\u00e5then G, Ferrara M, Keindl M, Ben-Menachem E, Tanasescu R, Brodtkorb E, Hillbom M, Leone MA, Ludolph AC. Alcohol withdrawal syndrome: mechanisms, manifestations, and management. Acta Neurol Scand. 2017 Jan;135(1):4-16. doi: 10.1111/ane.12671. Epub 2016 Sep 1. PMID: 27586815; PMCID: PMC6084325."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61190"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1819"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61190"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T14:13:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T14:18:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1819"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75672"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"